{{for|the 1968 American film|Chubasco (film)}}
A '''chubasco''' is a violent [[squall]] with thunder and lightning,<ref>http://ggweather.com/winds.html</ref> encountered during the rainy season along the Pacific coast of [[Mexico]], [[Central America]], and [[South America]]. It is also widely used when rain is accompanied by strong winds in other Spanish-speaking countries.

The word chubasco has its origins in the Portuguese word ''[[wiktionary:pt:chuva|chuva]]'' which means rain. The [[North American Monsoon|monsoon]]<ref>http://ag.arizona.edu/maricopa/garden/html/weather/monsoon.htm</ref> storms that regularly pass over the southwestern United States, including the Southern regions of Arizona and New Mexico, are sometimes referred to as Chubascos<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Hales | first1 = John E | year = 1975 | title = A Severe Southwest Desert Thunderstorm: 19 August 1973 | url = | journal = Mon. Wea. Rev. | volume = 103 | issue = | pages = 344–351 | doi = 10.1175/1520-0493(1975)103<0344:ASSDTA>2.0.CO;2 | bibcode = 1975MWRv..103..344H }}</ref><ref>''Mohave Daily Miner'', Sep 2, 1984.https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=943&dat=19840902&id=EIALAAAAIBAJ&sjid=S1MDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3278,11733</ref>In the northern parts of Mexico, especially the northeast and north central, the word chubasco is used especially for suddenly occurring localised storms that produce very strong winds, sometimes as much as 90 miles/hour, and intense rains of as much as 5 - 6 inches in less than an hour.  Straight-line winds can topple windmills, and break large limbs of large, sometimes ancient trees.The phenomena normally occurs during the hottest days of the year (May through October).

