[[Alaska]] has about 3,197 officially named natural [[lake]]s,{{Cref|C}}<ref>{{cite web
| title=Lakes in Alaska and in Juneau
| publisher=[[U.S. Board on Geographic Names]], [[United States Geological Survey]], [[Department of the Interior]]
| url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/pls/gnispublic/f?p=gnispq:2:::NO::P1_CLASS,P1_STATE:Lake,Alaska
}}</ref>{{Cref|B}} out of over 3,000,000 unnamed natural [[lake]]s,<ref>{{cite web
| title=Alaska Hydrologic Survey | publisher=[[Alaska Department of Natural Resources]]
| url=http://www.dnr.state.ak.us/mlw/water/hydro/
}}</ref> approximately 67 named artificial [[reservoir]]s,{{Cref|C}}<ref>{{cite web
| title=Reservoirs in Alaska
| publisher=[[U.S. Board on Geographic Names]], [[United States Geological Survey]], [[Department of the Interior]]
| url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/pls/gnispublic/f?p=gnispq:2:::NO::P1_CLASS,P1_STATE:Reservoir,Alaska
}}</ref> and 167 named dams.{{Cref|C}}<ref>{{cite web
| title=Dams in Alaska
| publisher=[[U.S. Board on Geographic Names]], [[United States Geological Survey]], [[Department of the Interior]]
| url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/pls/gnispublic/f?p=gnispq:2:::NO::P1_CLASS,P1_STATE:Dam,Alaska
}}</ref>
For named artificial reservoirs and dams, see the [[list of reservoirs and dams of Alaska]].

