{{Poland-scientist-stub}}

{{Infobox person | name = María Teresa Ruiz | image = María Teresa Ruiz, Premio Nacional de Ciencias Exactas (2).jpg | image_size = 250px | caption = María Teresa Ruiz in 2018 | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1946|09|24|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Santiago de Chile]] | death_date = | death_place = | death_cause = | residence = | other_names = | known_for = discovering kelu 1 | education = | employer = | occupation = | title = | salary = | networth = | height = | weight = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = | boards = | spouse = | partner = | children = | parents = | relatives = | signature = | website = | footnotes = | nationality = [[Chilean people|Chilean]] }}
'''María Teresa Ruiz''' (born 24 September 1946) is a [[Chile]]an [[astronomy|astronomer]]. She was the first woman to receive Chile's [[National Prize for Exact Sciences (Chile)|National Prize for Exact Sciences]].<ref name="UniversiaChile">{{cite web | last = Staff | first = | last2 = | first2 = | title = María Teresa Ruiz: Una mente brillante (A Beautiful Mind) | publisher = Universia Chile | date = 17 March 2005 | url = http://noticias.universia.cl/ciencia-nn-tt/noticia/2005/03/17/475754/maria-teresa-ruiz-mente-brillante.html | accessdate = 2012-10-20}} {{es icon}},</ref>
==Biography== Ruiz was born in [[Santiago de Chile]] in 1946. She was the first woman to successfully study astronomy at the [[University of Chile]],<ref name="UniversiaChile"/> the first female scientist to receive a PhD in astrophysics at Princeton University, and in 1997 became the first woman to receive her country's National Prize for Exact Sciences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.astro.princeton.edu/news/prof-maria-ruiz-princeton-phd-75-honored-loreal-unesco-women-science-award|title=Prof. Maria Ruiz, Princeton PhD '75, honored with Loreal-UNESCO For Women in Science Award {{!}} Department of Astrophysical Sciences|website=web.astro.princeton.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-05-18}}</ref> Also, she received a postdoctoral position at Tiestre Observatory, Ruiz worked for two years in UNAM, the Institute of Astronomy in Mexico.
Ruiz did research at [[Trieste]], [[Mexico]] and [[New York City]] before she gained a [[Guggenheim fellowship]]. She discovered [[Kelu-1|Kelu 1]], a [[brown dwarf]].<ref name="UniversiaChile"/>
{{as of|2016|May}}, she is a member of the [[Chilean Academy of Science]] and a professor at the [[University of Chile]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fis.com/fis/worldnews/worldnews.asp?l=e&id=84338&ndb=1 |title=Scientists to analyze possible red tide-salmon dumping link |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=May 17, 2016 |website= Fish Info & Services Co.Ltd|publisher= |access-date=May 26, 2016 |quote=}}</ref> where she teaches astronomy. She is also a member of the Centro de Astrofísica CATA (''CATA Centre for Astrophysics'').<ref>{{cite web|language=Spanish |url= http://www.academiadeciencias.cl/un-paseo-por-el-universo-profesora-maria-teresa-ruiz/|title="UN PASEO POR EL UNIVERSO", PROFESORA MARÍA TERESA RUIZ |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=September 7, 2015 |website=Chilean Academy of Science |publisher= |access-date=May 26, 2016 |quote=}}</ref>
==Awards== *Presidential Chair in Science, 1996 *Chancellor's Medal, University of Chile, 1996 *Sciences National Award, 1997 *Chancellor's Medal, University of Chile, 1998 *Fellow of the Academy of Sciences since, 1998 *Labarca Merit Award, 2000 *[[L'Oréal-UNESCO Awards for Women in Science]], 2017.<ref>[http://www.unesco.org/new/en/media-services/single-view/news/announcement_of_laureates_of_2017_loreal_unesco_for_wome/ Announcement of Laureates of 2017 L’Oréal-UNESCO For Women in Science Awards]</ref>
